---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;

const PLAYBOOK_BASE =
  "https://wenhaoyu-bryan.github.io/AI-PM-Operating-Playbook/en/workbench/";
---

<Layout
  title={`Vibe Coding for Product Discovery | ${config.site.title}`}
  description="PM-led, coding-agent-assisted prototyping for early discovery, workflow validation, and executable product communication."
>
  <Header />

  <Main pageTitle="Vibe Coding for Product Discovery" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Vibe coding, in this playbook, means PM-led, coding-agent-assisted
      prototyping. You pair with tools like Claude Code or Cursor to build
      functional prototypes through natural language — not to ship production
      code, but to discover, validate, and communicate product ideas faster.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">What It Means in This Playbook</h2>
    <p>
      The term "vibe coding" gets used loosely to describe any LLM-assisted
      coding. Here it means something specific: a PM using a coding agent to
      explore product ideas through working prototypes. The PM defines product
      intent, architecture constraints, and design boundaries. The agent
      generates code.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      This is not about replacing engineering. It is about adding a capability
      that traditional PM tooling — wireframes, slide decks, written PRDs — does
      not provide: the ability to produce something you can click through, test
      with stakeholders, and evaluate for technical feasibility before
      committing engineering resources.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Suitable Scenarios</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Early-stage ideas.</strong> You have a concept but need to see it
        as a working interface to know if it makes sense.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Workflow validation.</strong> You need to test whether a multi-step
        user flow works before writing a detailed spec.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Stakeholder communication.</strong> A clickable prototype communicates
        product intent more precisely than a slide deck.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Technical feasibility checks.</strong> You want to know whether an
        API integration or data flow is practical before requesting engineering time.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">What PM-Led Prototyping Improves</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Speed of iteration.</strong> A prototype that takes a PM hours with
        a coding agent might take weeks in a traditional sprint cycle. This speed
        changes how you explore ideas — you can test more hypotheses before committing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Quality of specifications.</strong> When you have built a working
        prototype, your PRDs become more concrete. You specify data models, API contracts,
        and interaction patterns because you have thought through them already.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Stakeholder alignment.</strong> Clickable prototypes reduce ambiguity.
        Stakeholders react to what they see, not what they imagine. Feedback becomes
        more specific and actionable.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">What It Does NOT Replace</h2>
    <p>Vibe coding for discovery has clear limits. It does not replace:</p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Production engineering.</strong> Discovery prototypes are not production-ready.
        They are disposable by design. The value is in the learning, not the code.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Architecture decisions.</strong> A PM can prototype a UI flow, but
        system architecture decisions — database design, service boundaries, scaling
        strategy — require engineering judgment.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Security review.</strong> Generated code does not go through threat
        modeling or security audit. Discovery prototypes must not handle real user
        data.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Scalability and performance.</strong> A prototype that works for one
        user with sample data may not work for thousands of users with real data.
        These are engineering problems, not discovery problems.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      Product Intent and Acceptance Criteria
    </h2>
    <p>
      The most important skill in PM-led vibe coding is not prompt crafting — it
      is product definition. Before you prompt the agent, you need to know:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>What user problem does this solve?</li>
      <li>What does the happy path look like?</li>
      <li>What data goes in and what comes out?</li>
      <li>What is "good enough" for a discovery prototype?</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2">
      The PM defines the "what" and the "why." The agent builds the "how." When
      you have clear acceptance criteria, the agent produces better output. When
      you do not, it produces something that looks right but does not solve the
      problem.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Prototype-to-Production Boundary</h2>
    <p>
      A discovery prototype answers the question: "Is this idea worth pursuing?"
      Once the answer is yes, the work shifts from discovery to delivery. This
      boundary matters because:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        Discovery code optimizes for speed and learning. Production code
        optimizes for reliability and maintainability.
      </li>
      <li>
        Discovery prototypes use sample data and skip edge cases. Production
        systems must handle real data and failure modes.
      </li>
      <li>
        The handoff from discovery to engineering should include the validated
        user flow, data model, and acceptance criteria — not the prototype code
        itself.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Common Failure Patterns</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Over-trusting generated code.</strong> A prototype that runs without
        errors is not necessarily correct. Verify product logic, not just syntax.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Skipping validation.</strong> A prototype that the PM built and tested
        alone is not validated. Put it in front of stakeholders and potential users.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Scope creep.</strong> Discovery prototypes should be small and focused.
        If you find yourself adding authentication, databases, and deployment pipelines,
        you have crossed into engineering work.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Confusing prototypes with products.</strong> The prototype's purpose
        is to generate learning. If the learning says "do not build this," that is
        a successful outcome.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      Connection to the Interactive Tool
    </h2>
    <p>
      The AI PM Operating Playbook helps you go from an idea to a structured
      product brief and a coding-agent handoff document. For vibe coding, this
      means you start with a structured framing instead of an open-ended prompt
      — which produces better prototypes, faster.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 mb-8">
      <a
        href={PLAYBOOK_BASE}
        class="bg-accent text-accent-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >
        Turn an idea into a structured product brief and handoff ↗
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/harness-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Harness Engineering
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/loop-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Loop Engineering
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/agent-product-design")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Agent Product Design
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
